<p>Nama has a fairly simple consonant system involving the normal non-clicks, but far more complex are the clicks, as shown above<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#accordion" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Ledefoged & Traill 1984">[1]</a></sup>. There are four types of articulation and five different accopaniment types.  Clicks are produced with two points of closure of the tongue, instead of one as non-clicks are formed.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#accordion" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Beach 1938:74">[2]</a></sup> When making a click, the air is drawn inward instead of outward. Clicks have four types of articulation with five different accompaniment types. Clicks appear only at the beginning of the root and are always followed by a vowel or diphthong, with the exception of neutral vowel.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#accordion" data-toggle="tooltip" title="Beach 1938:89">[3]</a></sup></p>